<div class="rules-container">
    <div class="rules-header">How to Wash the Deceased (Ghusl Mayyit)</div>

    <div class="rules-section">
        <h3>Introduction</h3>
        <p>Ghusl (ritual washing) of the deceased is a communal obligation (<strong>Fard Kifayah</strong>) in Islam. This process is to be done respectfully and in accordance with Islamic teachings from the Qur’an and Sunnah.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="rules-section">
        <h3>Who Should Perform Ghusl?</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Only practicing, trustworthy Muslims of the same gender as the deceased should perform the washing.</li>
            <li>For a male: preferably male family members or close friends.</li>
            <li>For a female: preferably female family members.</li>
            <li>Spouses are allowed to wash each other.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="rules-section">
        <h3>Materials Needed</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Warm water</li>
            <li>Sidr (lotus leaves powder) or mild soap</li>
            <li>Camphor (Kafoor) for the final rinse</li>
            <li>Disposable gloves</li>
            <li>Clean towels and sheets</li>
            <li>Private space with water drainage</li>
            <li>Perfume (e.g. non-alcoholic oud or itr)</li>
            <li>Three white shrouds (Kafan) for men, five for women</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="rules-section">
        <h3>Step-by-Step Procedure</h3>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Place the body respectfully</strong> on a clean table, covered from navel to knees for men and entire body for women.</li>

            <li><strong>Make the niyyah (intention)</strong>: silently intend to perform Ghusl for the sake of Allah and fulfilling the deceased’s right.</li>

            <li><strong>Wash the private parts</strong>: With gloves, wash the front and back private areas. Do not uncover more than necessary.</li>

            <li><strong>Perform Wudu (ablution)</strong>: as for prayer. Do not insert water into the nose or mouth—use damp cotton.</li>

            <li><strong>Wash the body</strong>: Start with the right side, then left. Use water mixed with Sidr (or soap) for first two washes.</li>

            <li><strong>Final wash with camphor water</strong>: Camphor has a cooling, fragrant effect. Use it in the final rinse.</li>

            <li><strong>Dry the body gently</strong> using clean towels.</li>

            <li><strong>Apply perfume</strong> (optional): Lightly apply itr on joints (e.g. hands, knees, forehead).</li>

            <li><strong>Wrap the body in the Kafan</strong>: Start with inner sheet, wrap tightly and respectfully. Use ties to secure ends.</li>
        </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="rules-section">
        <h3>Important Guidelines</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Maintain the dignity and privacy of the deceased throughout.</li>
            <li>Avoid excessive soap, water, or handling of the body.</li>
            <li>Say “Bismillah” before each stage and recite silent du‘a for forgiveness.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="rules-section">
        <h3>Special Cases</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Martyrs (Shaheed):</strong> Do not perform Ghusl; they are buried in their clothes.</li>
            <li><strong>Stillbirths:</strong> Ghusl is not mandatory for miscarried fetus unless it was alive for some time after birth.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="note-box">
        <strong>Note:</strong> This guide is based on authentic Islamic sources and practices. If uncertain, consult a local Islamic scholar or masjid for assistance. Every effort should be made to complete this duty with care, dignity, and sincerity.
    </div>
